{"cursor":"28192","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox disease\n| Name = Acromegaly Image = Acromegaly facial features.JPEG Caption = Facial\n| aspect of a patient with acromegaly. The cheekbones are pronounced, the\n| forehead bulges, the jaw is enlarged and facial lines prominent. DiseasesDB =\n| 114 ICD10 = ICD9 = ICDO = OMIM = 102200 MedlinePlus = 000321 eMedicineSubj =\n| med eMedicineTopic = 27 eMedicine_mult = MeshID = D000172\n}} 'Acromegaly' (; from Greek Î¬ÎºÏÎ¿Ï akros \"extreme\" or \"extremities\" and Î¼ÎµÎ³Î¬Î»Î¿Ï\nmegalos \"large\") is a syndrome that results when the anterior pituitary gland\nproduces excess growth hormone (GH) after epiphyseal plate closure at puberty. A\nnumber of disorders may increase the pituitary's GH output, although most\ncommonly it involves a GH-producing tumor called pituitary adenoma, derived from\na distinct type of cell (somatotrophs).\n\nAcromegaly most commonly affects adults in middle age, and can result\nin severe disfigurement, complicating conditions, and premature death if\nunchecked. Because of its pathogenesis and slow progression, the disease is hard\nto diagnose in the early stages and is frequently missed for years until changes\nin external features, especially of the face, become noticeable.\n\nAcromegaly is often associated with gigantism.\n","linknr":646,"url":"acromegaly","recorded":1362513108,"links":58,"instances":["wrestler","makeup_artist","the_addams_family","fighter","giant","tv_series","1984_film"],"pdf":["http://www.royalberkshire.nhs.uk/pdf/Acromegaly_jan11.pdf","http://www.springerlink.com/content/u7645787h2435373/fulltext.pdf"],"categories":["Endocrine-related cutaneous conditions","Growth disorders","Growth hormones","Neuroendocrinology","Pituitary disorders"],"headings":["Signs and symptoms","Causes","Complications","Diagnosis","Treatment","Pseudoacromegaly","Notable cases","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10